<TITLE> Australia PM suffers in polls after policy moves </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 SYDNEY, May 10 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Support for Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd has plunged and his Labour party is now on par with the opposition after controversial policy decisions unsettled voters in the leadup to elections, a fresh survey showed. Rudd's approval rating fell 14 percentage points to 45 percent while his disapproval rating jumped 13 points to 49 percent, with just months before elections, expected to be held in October, according to a Herald/Nielsen poll in Monday's Sydney Morning Herald. The poll also showed support for Rudd's Labor party at 50 percent on a two-party preferred basis, on par with the opposition, after Rudd announced a hefty mining tax hike, placed his emissions-trading scheme on hold, dropped a plan to expand childcare, hiked tobacco taxes, and axed a controversial home insulation scheme. The survey showed support for the new mining tax at 44 percent while 47 percent opposed it. A Newspoll survey last week showed support for the Labor government was down 5 points to 49 percent, while the conservatives soared 5 points to 51 percent after Rudd dropped several centrepiece policies that helped him win power in 2
